Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all existing agreements
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas announced at the UN General Assembly on Thursday that he would break all agreements with Israel if the country's future government tries to fulfill Benjamin Netanyahu's pledge to annex the occupied Palestinian lands.
“If the future government of Israel, as it will be formed, goes ahead with this plan, we will cancel all the agreements signed [with Israel] and we will withdraw from all the commitments we have made,” he said.
“We will reject the whole plan completely and completely,” Abbas said.
"It is our duty to defend all our rights by all possible means - no matter what the consequences - engaging fully in the implementation of international law and in the fight against terrorism," he said.
Netanyahu, Israel’s current prime minister, was re-elected after the September 17 elections.
A week before the election, he announced that if he wins, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to include all Jewish settlements across the West Bank in Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, then led by Yasser Arafat, signed a series of peace agreements sponsored by the United States.
The 84-year-old Abbas also promised to hold a general election in the Palestinian territories during a session of the UN General Assembly.
The last one took place in 2006.
“When I return home, I will call local elections in the West Bank, Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem, and all those who oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community,” he said.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer at the United Nations, to exercise the rights of “the rightful members of the United Nations and all its organs and institutions.”
The Palestinian leader concluded his speech with a call to the international community to “force Israel to comply with the provisions of the United Nations with all due respect.”
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas's speech, declaring that the Palestinian leader "would rather focus at the UN on the Palestinian Authority's efforts directed against Israel than to fight calls for terrorism in the Authority under his leadership."
Danon, however, did not refer to Netanyahu’s planned annexation of the occupied Palestinian lands.
