PLN 105 million for video game companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced the results of the 3rd edition of the GameINN programme on Friday.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by NCBR, there was, among others, the development of a platform for creating field games based on the AR game engine creating a map of the real world with an application enabling data transfer by users; a testing and training platform for verifying practical skills at the workplace and professional improvement using VR and AI technology; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using the new PBR platform.
The aim of the GameINN sector program is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish sector of video game producers on the global market by 2023.
According to NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 was PLN 2.23 billion.
“The specially prepared GameINN research agenda and support for entrepreneurs already reaching PLN 300 million under this sectorial program constitute an important impulse for the further, dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev,” the statement reads.
The video game industry is an excellent example of the effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
“Incentives for innovative entrepreneurs introduced by the government, such as R&D credits, competence improvement programs, IP box or support programs implemented by NCBR, drive companies’ innovative activities and allow them to compete more effectively in a very competitive market”, says Deputy Prime Minister Jarosław Gowin, Minister of Science and Higher Education.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of co-financing projects, but also remains in their pockets - three-quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R&D relief in 2018 than in the previous year.
“The amount of deductible costs related to R&D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which gave more than PLN 300 million of savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in three editions of GameINN”, emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
Director of NCBR Dr. Wojciech Kamieniecki reminds that in the two previous competitions, over PLN 211.2 million in funding was awarded to 78 innovative projects.
The great interest in the 3rd competition and the variety of applications submitted show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
“We are particularly pleased that among the selected projects, as in previous editions, there are projects concerning solutions serving not only entertainment, but also those related to Industry 4.0,” he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, business consortia and business consortia with scientific units could apply for funding of up to PLN 20 million.
The NCBR received 87 applications for a total amount of funding of approximately PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were granted almost PLN 105 million in co-financing.
Detailed information about the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sectoral programme is implemented as part of the Smart Growth Operational Programme.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated in the Polish Games Agreement, which includes such companies as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team and 11 bit studios.
