Majorca Counts Losses After Travel Agency Bankruptcy Thomas Cook
More than 25,000 foreign tourists will not be coming to Majorca in October as a result of the bankruptcy announced by Thomas Cook travel agency on Monday.
Marc Pons, a representative of the autonomous government of the Balearic Islands, said on Friday that among the 25,000 holidaymakers who will not be able to take their October vacation in Majorca, there were also people who were supposed to travel with companies indirectly associated with Thomas Cook, such as Neckermann.
Pons explained that 80 percent of the expected holidaymakers, who due to the bankruptcy of the British company had to give up their vacation in Mallorca next month, are citizens of Germany and Scandinavian countries.
However, according to Pons, due to the fact that Thomas Cook did not direct tourists to the Balearic island in November-April, the losses for the local economy will be less.
He revealed that the government of the Balearic Islands has already begun negotiations with international operators on "entering the Mallorca market" after the bankruptcy of the British operator.
According to the newspaper Diario de Mallorca, more than 1,000 people will lose their jobs in October due to the tourist crisis in Majorca.
Approximately 800 are laid off employees of the Thomas Cook office in Palma.
Other people will lose their jobs mainly in the hotel sector.
On Monday, with the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook in many hotels in Majorca, property owners demanded that guests pay an additional fee for accommodation.
This situation has been experienced, among others, by dozens of tourists from Poland.
The Balearic government estimates that by Thursday, dozens of hotels in Majorca had stopped operations at least until the end of October in connection with the bankruptcy declaration by Thomas Cook and the companies cooperating with him.
On Friday, the Diario de Ibiza newspaper reported that most of the Ibiza hotels that worked with the Thomas Cook group are not planning to close in the coming weeks.
The newspaper recalls that on this Balearic island, the British bankrupt cooperated with 42 hotels.
On Wednesday, the autonomous government of the Balearic Islands announced that it would ask the Spanish government to support the region with an amount of 100 million euros to cover losses caused by the bankruptcy of travel agency Thomas Cook.
They revealed that the most affected tourists in the archipelago, about 36,000 people, are in Majorca.
According to data from the government of the Balearic Islands, Thomas Cook owes local tourism companies, mainly hotel operators, about 5 million euros for the implementation of contracts for the period July-September 2019.
