Barbie against stereotypes.
Gender dolls
The manufacturer Barbie introduced a series of gender-neutral dolls to the market.
This is how he fights stereotypes.
The manufacturer Barbie has launched a series of gender-neutral dolls
In addition to Barbie with different skin color, figure or hairstyle, Mattel has introduced gender-neutral dolls for sale.
Toys from the "Creatable World" series wear wigs.
Children can therefore decide whether their Barbie is to have short hair or long hair.
Their wardrobe consists of both trousers and dresses.
In the blink of an eye, dolls can become boys and vice versa.
They are also available in different skin colors and with different clothes.
Gender dolls no longer have full lips, long lashes and a slim waist or, in the case of Ken, broad shoulders.
The company believes that children don’t like their dolls to have gender norms imposed, and some parents and feminists are convinced that toys made with a specific gender in mind inhibit girls’ ambitions and reinforce traditional stereotypes.
“The new dolls will make all children feel free,” says Mattel.
The Barbie doll, which appeared on the market in 1959 in a swimsuit and high-heeled shoes, has been repeatedly criticized in the past for promoting “unhealthy female stereotypes”, such as unnatural body proportions, for example.
The company responded to the criticism and has already launched dolls of different skin colors, as well as more rounded shapes.
There are also dolls in the hijab.
