Dakar: West Africa's largest mosque opened
Tens of thousands of people from all over Senegal gathered in the capital on Friday for the inauguration of a huge mosque, believed to be the largest in West Africa.
Muslims arrived by bus, car and on foot in the Bopp district, where a new mosque was built that could accommodate 30,000 worshippers.
The building was built by the Mouride Brotherhood, a Sufi Islamic movement that dominates Senegal.
Work on the mosque began ten years ago in a six-hectare wetland area donated by the government.
The name of the Massalikul Jinan mosque ("Paths to Paradise") is derived from the title of a poem by Sheikh Ahmadou Bamba Mbacke, a 19th-century founder of the brotherhood, revered by his followers as a saint.
The mosque is clad in Carrara marble and has five minarets.
The highest of them is 78 meters.
The mosque inside can accommodate 15,000 worshippers, and the other as many can stay on the outer esplanade.
In the richly finished interiors, you can admire the gilded dome, giant chandeliers and decorations handmade by Moroccan workers.
Builders claim that the mosque is the largest in West Africa, but the building still has no comparison to mosques in other regions.
In Morocco, the Hassan II Mosque in Casablanca can accommodate 105,000 worshippers.
The construction of the mosque, which cost more than 30 million euros, was funded by private donations.
The government, in addition to the land, funded lighting, sanitation and road works worth 10.5 million euros.
