These trees could disappear from Europe.
“42 per cent of the tree species that make up Europe’s state of the art are at risk,” warns the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in its Red Book of European Trees published on Friday.
At the top of the list are, among others, chestnuts and rowan.
IUCN, an organization based in Gland, Switzerland, is publishing a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
The study was carried out by experts who concluded that 42 percent of the 454 tree species found in Europe (and elsewhere) are “highly endangered”.
Among the causes, the Red Book lists the rapid growth of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
According to IUCN, 58% of species are at risk of extinction and 15% of trees and shrubs (66 species) are at risk of extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Book lists errors in the exploitation of trees, accelerated urbanization, over-intensive tree felling, followed by forest fires and changes in the European eco-system.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and lichens is also strongly threatened.
“The consequences of human activities lead to the gradual disappearance of European plant species and pose a danger to the extinction of important and underestimated varieties in Europe, which are the basis of European ecosystems and have an impact on the health of our planet,” concluded the report by Luc Bas, who heads the European Office of IUCN.
