GUS: Life is getting better in Poland
According to the report on household budgets published by the Central Statistical Office on Friday, 44% of households rated their financial situation as good or rather good last year.
The figure was 37.2% a year earlier, 33.5% in 2016, and never more than 30% since 2009, when the statistical office first examined the subjective assessment of the situation of households.
A total of 8.1% of households considered their financial situation to be bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2% a year earlier and more than 20% in 2009.
The material situation of self-employed households is the best.
In this group, more than 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good.
At the other extreme are the households of pensioners, where the percentage of such answers was only 18%.
The number of children also greatly influences the subjective assessment of the material situation of households.
The worst situation is experienced by single parents, of whom 32 percent declare a good or rather good financial situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among childless households it is 48.8%.
In these statistics, the effect of the 500+ program is clearly visible.
Before it was launched (in 2016), the worst financial situation was assessed by single parents and large families (with at least three children).
Improving subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid increase in income, primarily from work.
However, this is not all, because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good is growing faster than real income.
What is more, at the level of voivodships there is no clear relationship between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best ratings are formulated by the inhabitants of the Opolskie Voivodeship, where 48.9% of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
Next are Lubuskie (47.7%), Śląskie (47.6%), Mazowieckie (47.3%) and Zachodniopomorskie (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in Opole, disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) amounted to less than 94% of the national average last year, and in Lubusz it amounted to 98%.
The highest incomes were recorded in Mazowieckie (120% of the national average) and Śląskie (104%).
On average, in Poland, disposable income per person amounted to PLN 1,693 in 2018.
In real terms (after adjustment for the impact of price changes) it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Compared to previous years, the result is quite low.
In 2016, per capita income increased by 7%, and a year later by 6.3%.
While income growth slows, it also slows spending growth.
These amounted to PLN 1187 per person last year, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased by 1.9%, and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Surveys of household budgets suggest that the statistical household now spends 70.1% of its disposable income, while still in 2014 this share exceeded 80%, and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
