"Rzeczpospolita": Ignoring the order of a police officer will be punished
According to the newspaper, a police officer’s disregard of a warrant for certain conduct is to be a new type of offense, threatened with a fine, arrest, or restriction of liberty.
Police unions want to make such a change.
The idea went to the Parliamentary Committee on Petitions.
“The case is serious, because already every year more than half a million criminal cases go to Polish courts,” we read.
"Rzeczpospolita" has determined that the petition that the Independent Union of Police Officers is writing to MPs on the amendment of the Code of Offences has a chance to succeed.
The authors of the petition propose a new wording of Article 54a of the Code of Offences.
It would read: "Anyone who does not comply with the request or order of a public official, issued within the limits and on the basis of the provisions of the law, shall be liable to imprisonment, fine or restriction of liberty."
“Paragraph 3 of this provision provides for an identical penalty for those who, by failing to follow orders, prevent or hinder the performance of an official activity,” the journal states.
Sociologist Andrzej Kowalski told Rzeczpospolita that although he agrees with the main message of the proposal, he fears that if it is implemented, it could be used in political demonstrations.
“In situations of freedom demonstrations, it would be unfavourable and instead of easing the situation, they would exacerbate it,” he adds.
According to statistics provided by the newspaper, 86% of citizens positively assessed police interventions in 2018 and that each month the services take 1.5 million interventions in the city.
Buras is worried about Europe
Jáchym Topol has writing in his blood.
Among his ancestors are editors, translators, writers.
His father, Josef Topol, was one of the most important post-war Czech playwrights, today exchanged in a row with Václav Havel.
From the very beginning, Jáchym has been cursed with a talent that he tries to use.
After eight years, he returned with a "Sensitive Man".
The protagonists are Buras and Soňa with their two sons, who do not form a typical Czech family.
They are travelling actors, they travel around Europe.
He is a lover of Shakespeare and a thief, she is a one-eyed translator who does not part with a bottle of wine.
One of the boys from birth did not make a sound, and for the other time stopped in infancy.
But it is not the heroes who are the most important in this story.
All of them are just a background for observing the world in which there is no longer room for artistic nomads.
It's a world of stuffy provinces, a society of old, suspicious people, and promiscuous youth.
The “sensitive man” sometimes turns into an absurd theatre.
The narrative mimics the didascalia, and the conversations of the characters create this world.
The scene is a Europe full of fears for its future, but also constant questions about the past.
Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancels 105 flights due to bankruptcy of Thomas Cook
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has collapsed, its Belgian subsidiary Neckermann operates.
However, the company has problems.
Brussels Airlines has announced that it will cancel 105 flights in October due to the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also laid off 75 employees.
All trips with an office that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to get their money back.
The Ghent court also declared the three Belgian subsidiaries Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services bankrupt.
Currently, around 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips purchased from Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were expected to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, spokeswoman Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said the company was now "fully operational" despite the British company's bankruptcy announcement by its mother, which caused concern among employees and customers.
The office then reassured that customers who bought trips in it would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook, the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world, declared bankruptcy on the night of Sunday.
The immediate cause of the bankruptcy was the collapse on Sunday of last-chance talks with creditors and potential investors.
Creditors demanded that, in addition to the 900 million pound rescue plan agreed in August, the company raise an additional 200 million as collateral for the winter period, when travel agencies usually have lower turnovers.
However, the company's problems have been mounting for several years, resulting in a debt of up to 1.6 billion pounds.
