Goerlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for opinion
Free accommodation in exchange for a review - such an unusual offer was prepared for the newcomers German Goerlitz.
The action is to help fight the ongoing decline in the city’s population.
Goerlitz is the easternmost city in Germany.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, according to The Guardian, the city is facing significant problems.
The lowest wages in Germany are in Goerlitz.
The city is also facing a steady decline in population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which resulted in a 25 percent drop in the city’s population.
In 2013, it reached 54,000 people.
To combat depopulation, officials came up with the idea of offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 proposals have been submitted.
Two-thirds of them were made by residents of large cities.
People from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom were also interested in the program.
“When we applied, we thought that the program was to convince people to move to Goerlitz,” said one of the project participants.
“Now we feel it doesn’t matter if we stay here after four weeks or not,” he added.
The city has 7,000 vacant apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the national average.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main goal of the program is to get feedback from the program participants.
The information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
“We want to know more about what people need, and if they decide to move, what their motivation was,” said program manager Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas for attracting new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals for living and working in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in the American Tulsa in the state of Oklahoma.
